<subSubSection pageId="17" pageNumber="328" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="17.[151,1436,222,463]" pageId="17" pageNumber="328">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,266,222,247]" pageId="17" pageNumber="328">Diagnosis</emphasis>
. This species can be distinguished from all other Neotropical 
<taxonomicName box="[1006,1118,222,247]" class="Insecta" family="Ichneumonidae" genus="Epirhyssa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="328" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1006,1118,222,247]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="328">Epirhyssa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the combination of the following characters: 
<number box="[398,410,259,283]" pageId="17" pageNumber="328" value="1.0">1</number>
) occipital carina not joining hypostomal carina; 
<number box="[967,982,259,283]" pageId="17" pageNumber="328" value="2.0">2</number>
) hind tibia prominently swollen; and 
<number box="[1413,1427,259,283]" pageId="17" pageNumber="328" value="3.0">3</number>
) tergite I elongate, about 
<number box="[426,461,295,319]" pageId="17" pageNumber="328" value="3.2">3.2</number>
times as long as posteriorly broad; and 
<number box="[914,929,295,319]" pageId="17" pageNumber="328" value="4.0">4</number>
) strong median tubercle on the anterior edge of the clypeus.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
